<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1551,1756]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
This dark brown species (
<figureCitation box="[447,531,1551,1575]" captionStart="FIGURES 93 – 101" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1821,1844]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,193,1800]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 93 – 101. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. striatus female 93 – 96: 93. Dorsal view; 94. Antenna; 95. Mesonotum and metanotum; 96. Pronotum. H. brasiliensis female 97 – 100: 97. Dorsal view; 98. Antenna; 99. Head and pronotum; 100. Mesonotum and metanotum. H. flavidus female: 101. Antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280422/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number box="[502,531,1551,1575]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="93.0">93</number>
</figureCitation>
) has the antennae and mid &amp; hind tibiae extensively dark, and the mesonotum closely striate (
<figureCitation box="[320,404,1588,1612]" captionStart="FIGURES 93 – 101" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1821,1844]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,193,1800]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 93 – 101. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. striatus female 93 – 96: 93. Dorsal view; 94. Antenna; 95. Mesonotum and metanotum; 96. Pronotum. H. brasiliensis female 97 – 100: 97. Dorsal view; 98. Antenna; 99. Head and pronotum; 100. Mesonotum and metanotum. H. flavidus female: 101. Antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280422/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number box="[372,404,1588,1612]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="95.0">95</number>
</figureCitation>
). It is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[584,713,1588,1612]" class="Insecta" family="Heterothripidae" genus="Heterothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis box="[584,713,1588,1612]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having antennal segment III relatively long (
<figureCitation box="[1244,1324,1588,1612]" captionStart="FIGURES 93 – 101" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1821,1844]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,193,1800]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 93 – 101. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. striatus female 93 – 96: 93. Dorsal view; 94. Antenna; 95. Mesonotum and metanotum; 96. Pronotum. H. brasiliensis female 97 – 100: 97. Dorsal view; 98. Antenna; 99. Head and pronotum; 100. Mesonotum and metanotum. H. flavidus female: 101. Antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280422/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number box="[1295,1324,1588,1612]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="94.0">94</number>
</figureCitation>
) and sternal discal setae on abdomen. The males lack sternal pore plates and are similar to females in coloration.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
